## Context

When `OpenAlexResolver` returns a candidate, the response carries an
OpenAlex Work ID like `https://openalex.org/W2117548367`. The ID is:

- **Stable.** OpenAlex documents IDs as permanent. Unlike DOIs,
  which can change registrar or move, OAIDs rarely break.
- **A free pivot.** Knowing the OAID lets future MAIBA features
  query OpenAlex for citations, related works, full record updates,
  etc., without re-doing the title search.
- **Useful even for items with no DOI.** Many grey-lit reports
  appear in OpenAlex with an OAID but no DOI. Today we drop the
  OAID, then can't get back to the OpenAlex record cheaply.

The Item model has no field for it. We capture nothing. This ticket
adds the slot and the wiring.

## Actions

1. **`src/maiba/model.py`** — add an optional `OAID` field to `Item`:
   ```python
   class Item(BaseModel):
       ...
       OAID: str | None = Field(default=None, description="OpenAlex Work ID, e.g. W2117548367")
   ```
   Add `OAID` to `Item.mergeable_fields()` per ticket 0029, so the
   merge step writes it when present.

2. **`src/maiba/resolvers/openalex.py:_work_to_item`** — extract the
   OAID from `work["id"]`:
   ```python
   oa_url = work.get("id", "")  # "https://openalex.org/W2117548367"
   oaid = oa_url.rsplit("/", 1)[-1] if "openalex.org/" in oa_url else None
   ```
   Pass through to the constructed `Item`.

3. **`src/maiba/ris.py`** — RIS has no standard tag for OpenAlex IDs.
   Two options; executor decides:
   - **Option A: `C1`/`custom1`** (recommended) — rispy maps `C1` →
     `custom1`, explicitly designed for user-defined extension. No
     semantic collision risk with Zotero-exported records.
   - **Option B: `M1`/`note`** — rispy maps `M1` → `note` (scalar).
     Zotero gives `M1` type-dependent semantics (often "Number"); may
     collide with Zotero-exported issue numbers.

   Inspect `ArchiveCCS.ris` for existing C1/M1 lines before deciding.
   No collision risk observed for either in the test corpus currently.

   Whichever tag is chosen, rispy handles it natively — no custom
   parser needed, just wire `("OAID", "<rispy-key>")` in `_SCALAR_FIELDS`.

4. **Reading**: parse `M1` back into `Item.OAID` on RIS read so the
   roundtrip is stable.

5. **Tests**: extend `test_ris_roundtrip.py` to cover OAID write/read.
   Extend `test_resolve_openalex.py` to assert OAID is captured from
   real fixture responses (those JSON files already have `id` fields —
   e.g. `ashworth-2009-doi.json` has `"id": "https://openalex.org/W2018647518"`).

6. **`_MERGEABLE_FIELDS`**: add `"OAID"` to the tuple in `pipeline.py`
   after 0029 lands. Without this, the pipeline drops the OAID from
   candidate before writing output. This is the hard dependency on 0029.

## Test (TDD red step)

```python
# tests/test_oaid.py
from pathlib import Path
import json
import respx
from httpx import Response
from maiba.config import load_config
from maiba.model import Item
from maiba.resolvers.openalex import OpenAlexResolver
from maiba.ris import read_ris, write_ris

CFG = load_config(Path("config/maiba.yaml"))


@respx.mock
def test_openalex_resolver_captures_OAID():
    """Real fixture response carries 'id' = OpenAlex URL; resolver populates Item.OAID."""
    fixture = json.loads(
        Path("tests/fixtures/responses/openalex/ashworth-2009-doi.json").read_text()
    )
    respx.get(url__startswith="https://api.openalex.org/").mock(
        return_value=Response(200, json=fixture)
    )
    resolver = OpenAlexResolver(CFG)
    item = Item(TY="JOUR", TI="x", AU=[], PY=2009, DO="10.1016/j.egypro.2009.02.302")
    result = resolver.resolve(item)
    assert result.candidate.OAID and result.candidate.OAID.startswith("W")


def test_oaid_roundtrips_via_M1(tmp_path):
    """Item with OAID writes to RIS as M1 and reads back identical."""
    item = Item(TY="JOUR", TI="x", AU=["a"], PY=2020,
                OAID="W2117548367")
    path = tmp_path / "out.ris"
    write_ris([item], path)
    text = path.read_text()
    assert "M1  - W2117548367" in text
    [item2] = list(read_ris(path))
    assert item2.OAID == "W2117548367"


def test_existing_M1_preserved_on_roundtrip():
    """An RIS with M1 already populated must not be clobbered."""
    # ... write M1=foo, read, assert OAID==foo
    ...
```

## Exit criteria

- `make test` green; new tests pass.
- `make lint` green.
- After re-run on `ArchiveCCS.ris`: items resolved via OpenAlex have
  an `M1  - W…` line in the output RIS. Eyeball a few and verify the
  OAID URL `https://openalex.org/<value>` opens the correct record.
- ground-truth diff vs `ArchiveCCS-cleaned.ris`: M1 fields don't
  introduce false-positive deltas (they're additive — Zotero export
  may or may not have them).

## Out of scope

- Crossref. Crossref doesn't have its own work IDs distinct from
  DOIs — DOI is the identifier. So no symmetric capture needed for
  CrossrefResolver.
- Other identifiers (Semantic Scholar `corpus_id`, arXiv ID, PMID).
  When MAIBA grows new resolvers, each gets its own ticket. Today
  we only return OpenAlex and Crossref candidates.
- Pivoting via OAID (fetching citations, related works). Capture is
  the prerequisite. The pivot features come later, when there's a
  clear use case.
